Package edu.ncsu.csc216.pack_scheduler.course

Class Activity

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.ncsu.csc216.pack_scheduler.course.Activity
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Conflict
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Course
    public abstract class Activity
extends java.lang.Object
implements Conflict
    Abstract class for Events and Courses has methods to check conflicts between activities, display information in an activity, get and set titles, meeting days, times, check for duplicate activities, check equivalence, and get time and meeting days as strings
    Author:
    Mari Kilgus

      • checkConflict

        public void checkConflict​(Activity possibleConflictingActivity)
                   throws ConflictException
        The checkConflict() method is an instance method of Activity. That means it compares the current instance (i.e., this) with the parameter possibleConflictingActivity to see if there is any conflict in their days and times. If there is a conflict, the checked ConflictException is thrown. If there is no conflict, nothing happens and the statement in the client code following the call to checkConflict() is executed. Two Activity objects are in conflict if there is at least one day with an overlapping time. A time is overlapping if the minute is the same. For example, an Activity on Monday from 1:30PM-2:45PM would conflict with an Activity on Monday from 2:45PM-3:30PM because of the overlap on the 2:45 minute.
        Specified by:
        checkConflict in interface Conflict
        Parameters:
        possibleConflictingActivity - the activity to compare to for a possible conflict
        Throws:
        ConflictException - if there is at least one day with an overlapping time

      • isDuplicate

        public abstract boolean isDuplicate​(Activity activity)
        The check that is done at this portion of the code is to see if the Course to be added is a duplicate of a Course already in the schedule – see [UC4]. [UC6] describes a similar situation for Event. The idea of duplicate Courses and Events is different from the definition of equality in the equals() methods. Keeping a full comparison is beneficial for testing and may be useful in other situations. So now add a new abstract method to Activity that both Course and Event can implement. The method will check if some other Course or Event is a duplicate.
        Parameters:
        activity - an Event or Course to be checked for duplication
        Returns:
        true if the Course or Event is a duplicate

      • setMeetingDaysAndTime

        public void setMeetingDaysAndTime​(java.lang.String meetingDays,
                                  int startTime,
                                  int endTime)
        Sets the Activity's meeting days, startTime, and endTime. An IllegalArgumentException is thrown if days are invalid or start time is not between 0000 and 2359 (an invalid military time) or the end time is not between 0000 and 2359 or an invalid military time, or the end time is less than the start time (i.e., no overnight classes)
        Parameters:
        meetingDays - the meeting days
        startTime - the start time
        endTime - the end time
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if meeting days and times are invalid

      • getMeetingString

        public java.lang.String getMeetingString()
        If the meeting days are A, the details view shows Arranged. Otherwise, the meeting information shows the meeting days followed by the start time in standard time (e.g., 1:30PM), a dash, and the end time in standard time. Only AM and PM are used.
        Returns:
        meetingInfo meeting information as a string in standard time format rather than in military format
